ic and cultural entanglements of Atlantic travelers in and beyond the Darwin era, and invites us to attend more closely to the consequences of mobility and contact on disciplines and persons. Bringing together an innovative group of readings-from field journals, diaries, letters, and testimonies to novels, stage plays, and audio recordings-Farooq advocates for a reconsideration of science, personhood, and the priority of race for the field of American studies. Whether expressed as narratives of acculturation, or as acts of resistance against the camera, the pen, or the shackle, these stories of the studied subjects of the Atlantic world add a new chapter to debates about personhood and disciplinarity in this era that actively challenged legal, social, and scientific categorizations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-SA 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEthnologyzAmericaxHistoryy19th century. 0aEthnologyzAmericaxHistoryy20th century. 0aPersonsxPhilosophy. 0aPhilosophical anthropologyxHistoryy19th century. 0aPhilosophical anthropologyxHistoryy20th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311072898940uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479842865.001.0001zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479842865zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479842865/original  a978-3-11-072898-9 New York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA